WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:17.328
Three small tables on this dashboard quietly decide your
entire trade. Your stop, your target, and whether the
trade is even worth taking. If you've never placed a trade
in your life, stay with me, because by the end of this
you'll read them like a desk trader.

2
00:00:17.928 --> 00:00:43.368
First, the two numbers everything here is built on. They
come from a trader named John Sweeney, who realized in the
nineties that you learn more from how far a trade travels
than from whether it simply won or lost. MAE, maximum
adverse excursion, is the worst a trade went against you
before it resolved. That's your heat, your risk. MFE,
maximum favorable excursion, is the best it ran in your
favor. That's the profit that was on the table.

3
00:00:43.968 --> 00:01:11.904
Now the left table, Risk and MAE. It's the spread of all
your adverse excursions, and this is exactly where your
stop-loss should come from. See the Key MAE, the typical
heat a trade takes. Sweeney's whole insight was this. Set
your stop just beyond your normal heat, never inside it.
Place it tighter than the seventieth percentile, and
ordinary wiggle stops you out of trades that would have
won. Park it just past that level, and you survive about
seven trades in ten without getting shaken out.

4
00:01:12.504 --> 00:01:40.536
The middle table is the mirror image. Profit and MFE. And
this sets your target. The Key MFE is your realistic take-
profit. Here's the trap beginners fall into. They set a
target bigger than the trade ever actually reaches, so it
just sits there unfilled and turns back red. If your
average profit is far below your average MFE, you're
leaving money on the table. If your target sits above it,
you're dreaming. The thirtieth percentile is the
conservative target the large majority of trades will
reach.

5
00:01:41.136 --> 00:02:11.928
And here is the table that settles every argument.
Cashflow expected values. Because a target that hits often
is not automatically the one that makes money. Look at
this. The high-probability, tiny target is actually
negative, minus a hundred and forty three dollars. It wins
almost every time, but the wins are too small to pay for
the losses. The high expected-value target, at plus two
hundred and three, is where the math finally works. This
is the single most important idea in trading. Win rate is
not profit. Expectancy is.

6
00:02:12.528 --> 00:02:37.584
And your entry ties it all together, because MAE and MFE
are both measured from the very second you get in. A
sharper entry means less heat against you and more room in
your favor, which quietly improves every number on these
three tables. So here is your whole trade plan in one
breath. Your stop comes from MAE. Your target comes from
MFE. And the expected value tells you whether that target
is actually worth taking. Three small tables, one complete
plan.

7
00:02:38.184 --> 00:02:48.696
Read these three tables before every trade, and you stop
guessing. You're sizing your stop to reality, your target
to reality, and only taking the trades the math actually
rewards.
